{"title_page": "Mattias Marklund", "text_new": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Mattias Marklund.jpg|right|thumbnail|300px|Mattias Marklund]] -->\n'''Mattias Marklund''' (born 14 September 1974) is a guitarist who plays in [[Vintersorg]], [[Casket Casey]], [[The Derelict Dead]], and [[TME (band)|TME]]. He also did guest guitar work for [[Vintersorg]] bandmate, [[Andreas Hedlund]]'s [[progressive rock]] band, [[Waterclime]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===With Otyg===\n\n*Bergtagen (demo, 1995)\n*I Trollskogens Dr\u00f6mmande M\u00f6rker (demo, 1996)\n*Galders\u00e5ng till Bergfadern (demo, 1997)\n*[[\u00c4lvef\u00e4rd]] (full-length, 1998)\nSagovindars Boning (full-length, 1999)\n\n===With Vintersorg===\n\n*[[Cosmic Genesis]] (full-length, 2000)\n*[[Visions from the Spiral Generator]] (full-length, 2002)\n*[[The Focusing Blur]] (full-length, 2004)\n*[[Solens r\u00f6tter]] (full-length, 2007)\n*[[Jordpuls]] (full-length, 2011)\n*[[Naturb\u00e5l]] (full-length, 2014)\n*[[Till fj\u00e4lls: Del II]] (full-length, 2017)\n\n===With Casket Casey===\n\n*[[Coffin' up Bones]] (EP, 2004)\n\n===With Waterclime===\n\n*[[The Astral Factor]] (full-length, 2006)\n\n===With TME===\n\n*[[Worlds Collide (TME album)|Worlds Collide]] (full-length, 2007)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060710213609/http://tme.deagol.net/ TME] (dead)\n*[http://www.casketcasey.com Casket Casey]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181215230753/http://vintersorganic.com/ Vintersorg]\n*[http://www.aphoticrecords.net Aphotic Records]\n*[http://www.bloodandgutsrecords.com Blood and Guts Records]\n\n{{Vintersorg}}\n{{Otyg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marklund, Mattias}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n\n\n{{Sweden-guitarist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Mattias Marklund.jpg|right|thumbnail|300px|Mattias Marklund]] -->\n'''Mattias Marklund''' (born 14 September 1974) is a guitarist who plays in [[Vintersorg]], [[Casket Casey]], [[The Derelict Dead]], and [[TME (band)|TME]]. He also did guest guitar work for [[Vintersorg]] band mate, [[Andreas Hedlund]]'s [[progressive rock]] band, [[Waterclime]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===With Otyg===\n\n*Bergtagen (demo, 1995)\n*I Trollskogens Dr\u00f6mmande M\u00f6rker (demo, 1996)\n*Galders\u00e5ng till Bergfadern (demo, 1997)\n*[[\u00c4lvef\u00e4rd]] (full-length, 1998)\nSagovindars Boning (full-length, 1999)\n\n===With Vintersorg===\n\n*[[Cosmic Genesis]] (full-length, 2000)\n*[[Visions from the Spiral Generator]] (full-length, 2002)\n*[[The Focusing Blur]] (full-length, 2004)\n*[[Solens r\u00f6tter]] (full-length, 2007)\n*[[Jordpuls]] (full-length, 2011)\n*[[Naturb\u00e5l]] (full-length, 2014)\n*[[Till fj\u00e4lls: Del II]] (full-length, 2017)\n\n===With Casket Casey===\n\n*[[Coffin' up Bones]] (EP, 2004)\n\n===With Waterclime===\n\n*[[The Astral Factor]] (full-length, 2006)\n\n===With TME===\n\n*[[Worlds Collide (TME album)|Worlds Collide]] (full-length, 2007)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060710213609/http://tme.deagol.net/ TME] (dead)\n*[http://www.casketcasey.com Casket Casey]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181215230753/http://vintersorganic.com/ Vintersorg]\n*[http://www.aphoticrecords.net Aphotic Records]\n*[http://www.bloodandgutsrecords.com Blood and Guts Records]\n\n{{Vintersorg}}\n{{Otyg}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marklund, Mattias}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n\n\n{{Sweden-guitarist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:-,typo(s) fixed: band mate \u2192 bandmate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mattias_Marklund"}
{"title_page": "Madalaine", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Madalaine\n| cover      = Madalaine_Winger.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Winger (band)|Winger]]\n| album      = [[Winger (album)|Winger]]\n| B-side     = Higher and Higher\n| released   = May 1988\n| format     = [[7-inch single|7\"]], [[CD single|CD]], [[Cassette single|Cass]]\n| recorded   = 1988\n| studio     = [[Atlantic Studios]], [[New York City]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:44\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = [[Kip Winger]], [[Reb Beach]], [[Beau Hill]]\n| producer   = [[Beau Hill]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Seventeen (Winger song)|Seventeen]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\n\"'''Madalaine'''\" is the debut single by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Winger (band)|Winger]], from their self-titled debut album ''[[Winger (album)|Winger]]''. Released in 1988, the song reached #27 on the [[Mainstream rock]] [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]]. According to [[Kip Winger]], it was one of the first four songs he and bandmate [[Reb Beach]] wrote when they first got together, based on a handful of riffs Reb had from when he was younger. Kip figured out how best to arrange the riffs, enabling the pair to complete the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccbanana.com/sludge/rewindkipwinger.htm |title=Metal Sludge Rewind with Kip Winger |publisher=Metal Sludge |accessdate=2009-01-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101015859/http://www.ccbanana.com/sludge/rewindkipwinger.htm |archivedate=2009-01-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n;7\" single\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| note1    = LP Version\n| length1  = 3:41\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| note1    = Radio Edit\n| length1  = 3:25\n}}\n\n;Cassette single\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| length1  = 3:41\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title2   = Higher and Higher\n| length2  = 3:18\n}}\n\n;CD single\n{{track listing\n| title1  = Madalaine\n| note1   = Radio Edit\n| length1 = 3:25\n| title2  = Madalaine\n| note2   = LP Version\n| length2 = 3:41\n| title3  = [[Seventeen (Winger song)|Seventeen]]\n| note3   = LP Version\n| length3 = 4:04\n}}\n\n;Promo CD single\n{{track listing\n| title1  = Madalaine\n| note1   = LP Version\n| length1 = 3:43\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1988)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />Position\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/winger/chart-history/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Winger Chart History|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Winger}}\n\n[[Category:1988 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Beau Hill]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Beau Hill]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kip Winger]]\n[[Category:Winger (band) songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Madalaine\n| cover      = Madalaine_Winger.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Winger (band)|Winger]]\n| album      = [[Winger (album)|Winger]]\n| B-side     = Higher and Higher\n| released   = May 1988\n| format     = [[7-inch single|7\"]], [[CD single|CD]], [[Cassette single|Cass]]\n| recorded   = 1988\n| studio     = [[Atlantic Studios]], [[New York City]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:44\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = [[Kip Winger]], [[Reb Beach]], [[Beau Hill]]\n| producer   = [[Beau Hill]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Seventeen (Winger song)|Seventeen]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\n\"'''Madalaine'''\" is the debut single by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Winger (band)|Winger]], from their self-titled debut album ''[[Winger (album)|Winger]]''. Released in 1988, the song reached #27 on the [[Mainstream rock]] [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]]. According to [[Kip Winger]], it was one of the first four songs he and band mate [[Reb Beach]] wrote when they first got together, based on a handful of riffs Reb had from when he was younger. Kip figured out how best to arrange the riffs, enabling the pair to complete the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccbanana.com/sludge/rewindkipwinger.htm |title=Metal Sludge Rewind with Kip Winger |publisher=Metal Sludge |accessdate=2009-01-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101015859/http://www.ccbanana.com/sludge/rewindkipwinger.htm |archivedate=2009-01-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n;7\" single\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| note1    = LP Version\n| length1  = 3:41\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| note1    = Radio Edit\n| length1  = 3:25\n}}\n\n;Cassette single\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1   = Madalaine\n| length1  = 3:41\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title2   = Higher and Higher\n| length2  = 3:18\n}}\n\n;CD single\n{{track listing\n| title1  = Madalaine\n| note1   = Radio Edit\n| length1 = 3:25\n| title2  = Madalaine\n| note2   = LP Version\n| length2 = 3:41\n| title3  = [[Seventeen (Winger song)|Seventeen]]\n| note3   = LP Version\n| length3 = 4:04\n}}\n\n;Promo CD single\n{{track listing\n| title1  = Madalaine\n| note1   = LP Version\n| length1 = 3:43\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1988)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />Position\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/winger/chart-history/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks|title=Winger Chart History|accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Winger}}\n\n[[Category:1988 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Beau Hill]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Beau Hill]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kip Winger]]\n[[Category:Winger (band) songs]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:-,typo(s) fixed: band mate \u2192 bandmate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madalaine"}
{"title_page": "Baldia Town", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->| name                            = Baldia Town<br>{{nq|\u0628\u0644\u062f\u06cc\u06c1 \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646}}\n| settlement_type                 = [[Towns in Karachi|Constituent Town of Karachi]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->| image_skyline                   = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_map                       = Baldia Town Karachi.PNG\n| map_caption                     = Baldia Town was divided into 8 Union Councils\n<!-- Location ------------------>| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[Pakistan]]\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Sindh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = City District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Karachi, Sindh, Pakistan]]\n| parts_type                      = Union Councils\n| parts_style                     = list, coll\n| parts                           = 8\n| p1                              = [[Ittehad Town]]<br>[[Gulshan-e-Ghazi]]<br>[[Islamnagar (Karachi)|Islam Nagar]]<br>[[Muhajir Camp]]<br>[[Muslim Mujahid Colony]]<br>[[Nai Abadi]]<br>[[Rasheedabad]]<br> [[Saeedabad, Karachi|Saeedabad]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = Town Council\n| leader_title1                   = Constituency\n| leader_name1                    = [[NA-249 (Karachi West-II)]]\n| leader_title2                   = National Assembly Member\n| leader_name2                    = [[Faisal Vawda]] ([[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|PTI]])\n| established_title               = Established\n| established_date                = August 2011\n| area_magnitude                  = 1 E+6\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_